[3] Italy: 236 305 total cases, 34 223 deaths
A. Daily update for 12 Jun 2020
Date: Fri 12 Jun 2020
Source: Italian Government Health Ministry [in Italian, machine trans. edited]
http://www.salute.gov.it/portale/nuovocoronavirus/dettaglioNotizieNuovoCoronavirus.jsp?lingua=italiano&menu=notizie&p=dalministero&id=4885


The increase in new cases of COVID-19 is +163 compared with +379 yesterday [11 Jun 2020]. This is what can be seen from the health monitoring data on the spread of the new coronavirus released at 18:00 CET on [12 Jun 2020].

- 236 305 cumulative cases, increase of 163 from 11 Jun 2020;
- 28 997 people are currently positive for the virus;
- 173 085 people have recovered;
- 3893 patients are hospitalized with symptoms, 227 in intensive care, and 24 877 are in home isolation;
- 34 223 deaths have been reported; however, this number can be confirmed only after the Istituto Superiore di Sanita has established the actual cause of death.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Italy is now 236 305 cases, including 34 223 deaths, up by 163 cases and 56 deaths in the past 24 hours. The previous day's (11 Jun 2020) 24-hour change was 379 cases and 53 deaths. The numbers of hospitalized cases and cases in the ICU are still in decline. As it has been, the major increase in cases was in Lombardy, reporting 272 newly confirmed cases.

Cases still continue to be concentrated in Lombardy, the original epicenter of the outbreak, Emilia-Romagna, Lazio, Piedmont, and Liguria (see tables at http://www.salute.gov.it/imgs/C_17_notizie_4885_0_file.pdf and http://www.salute.gov.it/imgs/C_17_notizie_4885_1_file.pdf). Lombardy again reported the largest number of newly confirmed cases in the 24-hour period (272) and was the only province reporting more than 50 new cases. Also, 16 provinces reported fewer than 10 newly confirmed cases (7 provinces reported no new cases), with another 3 provinces reporting fewer than 50 newly confirmed cases. Campania reported a decrease of 229 cases without an explanation.

The top 5 provinces by cumulative case count remain unchanged and are Lombardy, followed by Piedmont, Emilia-Romagna, Veneto, and Tuscany. The top 5 provinces by number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours are Lombardy (272), followed by Emilia-Romagna (33), Piedmont (31), Lazio (27), and Liguria and Tuscany, both with 7 cases each.

Italy is now 39 days post phase 2 initial opening up and 23 days post 2nd stage of phase 2 opening up. See summary observations of the Ministry of health in section B, immediately below.

A map of Italy showing regions can be seen at https://www.mapsofworld.com/italy/regions.html and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7464550,75. - Mod.MPP]

B. Monitoring report
Date: 12 Jun 2020
Source: Italy MOH [in Italian, machine trans, edited]
http://www.salute.gov.it/portale/nuovocoronavirus/dettaglioNotizieNuovoCoronavirus.jsp?lingua=italiano&menu=notizie&p=dalministero&id=4891


Key points
----------
- The analysis of the data relates to the period 1-7 Jun 2020, following the 2nd reopening phase that took place on 18 May 2020. For the times that elapse between exposure to the pathogen and the development of symptoms and between these and the diagnosis and subsequent notification, probably many of the cases reported this week contracted the infection 2-3 weeks before, i.e., between the 1st and 2nd reopening phases (between 11 and 25 May 2020).

- Overall, the picture of the transmission and impact of SARS-CoV-2 infection in Italy remains low critical. There is a general decrease in the number of cases and an absence of signs of overload of the assistance services.

- In some regional situations, the number of new cases reported each week is still high, albeit decreasing. This should call for caution, as it indicates that in some parts of the country the circulation of SARS-CoV-2 is still relevant.

- Furthermore, in almost the whole Peninsula, new cases of infection were diagnosed in the monitoring week. This finding, which is largely due to the intense screening and investigation of cases with identification and monitoring of close contacts, nevertheless highlights how the epidemic of COVID-19 in Italy has not ended.

- It is essential to keep attention high and to continue to strengthen testing-tracing-tracking activities in order to identify all potential transmission outbreaks early and continue to control the epidemic.

- It is also essential to maintain the general population's awareness of the fluidity of the epidemiological situation and the importance of continuing to rigorously comply with all the measures necessary to reduce the risk of transmission such as individual hygiene and physical distancing.

Conclusions
-----------
- The lock-down measures in Italy have effectively allowed a control of SARS-CoV-2 infection on the national territory even in a context of persistent widespread transmission of the virus with a very different incidence in the 21 Regions/PPAA. The situation described in this report, mainly relating to the period between the 1st and the 2nd transition phases, is overall positive.

- Transmission signals remain with new cases diagnosed in the monitoring week and with possible outbreaks. This describes a still epidemiologically fluid situation that requires rigorous compliance with the measures necessary to reduce the risk of transmission such as individual hygiene and physical spacing.

- It is necessary to maintain the resilience of local services high to continue promoting awareness and compliance of the population, to carry out active research and diagnostic assessment of potential cases, the isolation of confirmed cases, the quarantine of their close contacts. These actions are essential to control transmission and possibly quickly identify and deal with epidemic outbreaks.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Lessons to be learned: Time will tell as to whether there are increases slowing starting up in the previous high zones of transmission. Note that there are separate regional reports that can be linked to from the source URL page. - Mod.MPP]

